## 🐇 UDP — The Speedy, Simple Option

**Connectionless**. Sends datagrams independently — no handshake, no guarantees.

| Feature | Behavior |
|---|---|
| Connection | None — each datagram independent |
| Reliability | None — no ACKs, no retransmission |
| Ordering | Not guaranteed |
| Flow/Congestion control | None |
| Header size | 8 bytes (vs TCP's 20+ bytes) |

### UDP Trade-offs
- ❌ No reliability — app must build its own if needed
- ❌ No flow/congestion control — can flood receiver or network
- ✅ Simplicity and speed — ideal for time-sensitive apps

---

## ⚖️ TCP vs UDP — Side by Side

| Feature | TCP | UDP |
|---|---|---|
| Reliability | High (guaranteed) | Low (best-effort) |
| Ordering | Guaranteed | Not guaranteed |
| Connection | Connection-oriented (handshake) | Connectionless |
| Speed | Slower (overhead) | Faster (minimal overhead) |
| Overhead | High | Low |
| Flow control | Yes | No |
| Congestion control | Yes | No |
| Use cases | HTTP/S, SMTP, FTP, SSH | Streaming, gaming, DNS, VoIP, DHCP |

### Why each app picks what it picks

| App | Protocol | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Web browsing (HTTP/S) | TCP | Missing HTML/CSS breaks the page — must be complete & ordered |
| Video streaming (Netflix/YouTube) | UDP (often RTP-based) | A dropped frame > a full pause waiting for retransmit |
| Online gaming | UDP | Low latency > guaranteed delivery of every packet |
| DNS | UDP (TCP fallback for large responses/zone transfers) | Query is small & fast; client just re-sends if lost |
| VoIP | UDP | Brief audio dropout beats unacceptable delay |

