## 🏗️ Architecture-Level View

### TCP — A State Machine
Maintains real per-connection state:
- **Connection states:** CLOSED, LISTEN, SYN-SENT, SYN-RECEIVED, ESTABLISHED, FIN-WAIT-1/2, CLOSE-WAIT, CLOSING, LAST-ACK, TIME-WAIT
- **Sequence numbers**, **window sizes** (receive window, congestion window, slow-start threshold), **timers** (retransmission, keep-alive), **send/receive buffers**

**TCP Header (simplified):** Source/Dest Port, Sequence Number, Acknowledgment Number, Data Offset, Flags (URG/ACK/PSH/RST/SYN/FIN/ECE/CWR), Window Size, Checksum, Urgent Pointer, Options, Payload.

### UDP — Stateless Simplicity
No connection info kept — each datagram independent.

**UDP Header (simplified):** Source/Dest Port, Length, Checksum (optional — zero = not computed), Payload.

### Architectural Implications

| Aspect | TCP | UDP |
|---|---|---|
| Resource use | Higher (memory/CPU for state) | Lower (stateless) |
| Scalability | Harder for massive concurrent connections | Better for large-scale/real-time apps |
| Firewalls | Stateful — tracks connections, auto-allows return traffic | Often allowed by port only, no true "connection" tracking |
| IDS/IPS | Can analyze sequences/state for anomalies | Harder — no inherent order/reliability to check against |
| App responsibility | Mostly handled by TCP itself | App must handle: reassembly, error correction, retransmission, rate limiting |

